I was disappointed with this recipe. I utilized the advice to mix the rhubarb with sugar prior to preparation. - The Rhubarb turned out fine. But the cake was very buttery and unexciting. Overall the recipe is too many dishes to clean, for a mediocre outcome. For using rhubarb, I plan to return to the standards of either an oats/granola based cobbler or a true shortcake, with the rhubarb compote composed in a sauce pan separately.

Rating: 3
This is a very good, old-fashioned tasting dessert that's extremely flexible. I was short a cup of rhubarb so I made up the difference with an apple. Then I added too much sugar so I topped the rhubarb/apple mixture with a cup of frozen cranberries. I also added a teaspoon of vanilla and half a teaspoon of salt to the cake batter and overall, it was delicious! I'm looking forward to trying it again just with rhubarb.

Rating: 4
Delicious! Served this with vanilla ice cream, and we had the leftovers for breakfast.

Rating: 3
This recipe is almost identical to one that's been handed down in my family for four generations. (We like less sugar in our rhubarb - but the "sponge" part is the same.) A tip - if you toss the rhubarb with the sugar and let it sit for a couple hours, it'll juice (just like strawberries). That way, you can dispense with the water and use far less brown sugar, producing a nicer consistency. Ice cream is a perfect complement!

Rating: 3
This is quick, tasty and homey. The cake is very buttery, and it complements the sweet'n'tart fruit on the bottom very well. I added about a quart of sliced strawberries and made 150% of the cake recipe, which came out about right, I think. I also added about a teaspoon of vanilla to the fruit, and I sprinkled about two tablespoons of turbinado sugar on top of the cake for a pretty sparkly effect.

